doc.after: Significant Roman finds include parts of shops and houses that would have fronted onto Ermine Street, down which Roman armies marched to and from the Legionary Fortress at Lincoln.[5][7] The city of Lincoln was very important at that time, probably the capital of the late Roman Province of Flavia Caesariensis.[8] Evidence suggests that Navenby was a significant staging point along Ermine Street.[5] The Romans are reported to have maintained a small base or garrison in the village, and a possible Romano-British temple and burial sites have been unearthed in the area.[7] A 2009 archaeological dig uncovering a road, building foundations and Roman graves along with pottery and coins, showed Navenby to be a Roman Service Station.[9]
